6 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 160D-101 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 160D-101. Application.
8 (a) The provisions of this Article shall apply to all development regulations and programs
9 adopted pursuant to this Chapter or applicable or related local acts. To the extent there are
10 contrary provisions in local charters or acts, G.S. 160D-111 is applicable unless this Chapter
11 expressly provides otherwise. The provisions of this Article also apply to any other local
12 ordinance that substantially affects land use and development.
13 (b) The provisions of this Article are supplemental to specific provisions included in
14 other Articles of this Chapter. To the extent there are conflicts between the provisions of this
15 Article and the provisions of other Articles of this Chapter, the more specific provisions shall
16 control.control, unless a less specific enactment of the General Assembly clearly shows a
17 legislative intent to repeal or supersede the more specific provisions.
18 (c) Local governments may also apply any of the definitions and procedures authorized
19 by this Chapter to any ordinance that does not substantially affect land use and development
20 adopted under the general police power of cities and counties, Article 8 of Chapter 160A of the
21 General Statutes and Article 6 of Chapter 153A of the General Statutes respectively, and may
22 employ any organizational structure, board, commission, or staffing arrangement authorized by
23 this Chapter to any or all aspects of those ordinances.
24 (d) This Chapter does not expand, diminish, or alter the scope of authority for planning
25 and development regulation authorized by other Chapters of the General Statutes.
26 (e) Except as provided by local act, notwithstanding any other provision of law, a local
27 government may not exercise development regulation authority except as expressly authorized
28 by this Chapter. If State law governs a particular subject matter related to a local development
29 regulation authority, a local government shall not enact or enforce development regulations more
30 restrictive than those established by State law, unless the development regulation pertains to
31 floodplain management regulations as described in G.S. 143-138(e)."
