19 SECTION 7. G.S. 160D-402, as amended by S.L. 2024-49, reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 160D-402. Administrative staff.
21 (a) Authorization. – Local governments may appoint administrators, inspectors,
22 enforcement officers, planners, technicians, and other staff to develop, administer, and enforce
23 development regulations authorized by this Chapter. Local governments shall designate at least
24 one staff member charged with making determinations under that local government's
25 development regulations for purposes of G.S. 160D-703.
26 (b) Duties. – Duties assigned to staff may include, but are not limited to, drafting and
27 implementing plans and development regulations to be adopted pursuant to this Chapter;
28 determining whether applications for development approvals are complete; receiving and
29 processing applications for development approvals; providing notices of applications and
30 hearings; making decisions and determinations regarding development regulation
31 implementation; determining whether applications for development approvals meet applicable
32 standards as established by law and local ordinance; conducting inspections; issuing or denying
33 certificates of compliance or occupancy; enforcing development regulations, including issuing
34 notices of violation, orders to correct violations, and recommending bringing judicial actions
35 against actual or threatened violations; keeping adequate records; and any other actions that may
36 be required in order adequately to enforce the laws and development regulations under their
37 jurisdiction. A development regulation may require that designated staff members take an oath
38 of office. The local government shall have the authority to enact ordinances, procedures, and fee
39 schedules relating to the administration and the enforcement of this Chapter. The administrative
40 and enforcement provisions related to building permits set forth in Article 11 of this Chapter shall
41 be followed for those permits.
42 (c) Alternative Local Government Staff Arrangements. – A local government may enter
43 into contracts with another city, county, or combination thereof under which the parties agree to
44 create a joint staff for the enforcement of State and local laws specified in the agreement. The
45 governing boards of the contracting parties may make any necessary appropriations for this
46 purpose.
47 In lieu of joint staff, a governing board may designate staff from any other city or county to
48 serve as a member of its staff with the approval of the governing board of the other city or county.
49 A staff member, if designated from another city or county under this section, subsection, shall,
50 while exercising the duties of the position, be considered an agent of the local government
51 exercising those duties. The governing board of one local government may request the governing
