18 SECTION 9. G.S. 160D-605(a) reads as rewritten:
19 "(a) Plan Consistency. – When adopting or rejecting any zoning text or map amendment,
20 the governing board shall approve a brief statement describing whether its action is consistent or
21 inconsistent with an adopted comprehensive or land-use plan. The requirement for a plan
22 consistency statement may also be met by a clear indication in the minutes of the governing board
23 that at the time of action on the amendment the governing board was aware of and considered
24 the planning board's recommendations and any relevant portions of an adopted comprehensive
25 or land-use plan. If a zoning map amendment is adopted and the action was deemed inconsistent
26 with the adopted plan, the zoning amendment has the effect of also amending any future land-use
27 map in the approved plan, and no additional request or application for a plan amendment is
28 required. A plan amendment and a zoning amendment may be considered concurrently. The plan
29 consistency statement is not subject to judicial review. If a zoning map amendment qualifies as
30 a "large-scale rezoning" under G.S. 160D-602(b), the governing board statement describing plan
31 consistency may address the overall rezoning and describe how the analysis and policies in the
32 relevant adopted plans were considered in the action taken."
33 SECTION 10. G.S. 160D-701 reads as rewritten:
34 "§ 160D-701. Purposes.
35 Zoning regulations shall be made in accordance with a comprehensive plan and shall be
36 designed to promote the public health, safety, and general welfare. reflect the actual and
37 legitimate needs of the community. To that end, the regulations may address, among other things,
38 the following public purposes: to provide adequate light and air; to prevent the overcrowding of
39 land; to avoid undue concentration of population; to lessen congestion in the streets; to secure
40 safety from fire, panic, and dangers; to facilitate the efficient and adequate provision of
41 transportation, water, sewerage, schools, parks, and other public requirements; and to promote
42 the health, safety, morals, or general welfare actual and legitimate needs of the community. The
43 regulations shall be made with reasonable consideration, among other things, as to the character
44 of the district and its peculiar suitability for particular uses and with a view to conserving the
45 value of buildings and encouraging the most appropriate use of land throughout the local
46 government's planning and development regulation jurisdiction. The regulations may not include,
47 as a basis for denying a zoning or rezoning request from a school, the level of service of a road
48 facility or facilities abutting the school or proximately located to the school."
49 SECTION 11. G.S. 160D-702 reads as rewritten:
