46 SECTION 12. G.S. 160D-703 reads as rewritten:
47 "§ 160D-703. Zoning districts.
48 (a) Types of Zoning Districts. – A Except as provided in subsection (a1) of this section,
49 a local government may divide its territorial jurisdiction into zoning districts of any number,
50 shape, and area deemed best suited to carry out the purposes of this Article. Within those districts,
51 it may regulate and restrict the erection, construction, reconstruction, alteration, repair, or use of
Page 10 House Bill 765-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 buildings, structures, or land. Zoning By illustration, zoning districts may include, but are not be
2 limited to, include any of the following:
3 (1) Conventional districts, in which a variety of uses are allowed as permitted uses
4 or uses by right and that may also include uses permitted only with a special
5 use permit.
6 (2) Conditional districts, in which site plans or individualized development
7 conditions are imposed.
8 (3) Form-based districts, or development form controls, that address the physical
9 form, mass, and density of structures, public spaces, and streetscapes.
10 (4) Overlay districts, in which different requirements are imposed on certain
11 properties within one or more underlying conventional, conditional, or
12 form-based districts.
13 (5) Districts allowed by charter.
14 (a1) Residential Zoning Districts Classified Based on Density. – A local government shall
15 classify residential zoning districts based on the number of dwelling units allowed per acre. A
16 local government shall not classify residential zoning districts based on the minimum lot size
17 allowed in the district.
18 (a2) Permitted Uses in Counties. – In areas zoned for residential use, a county zoning
19 regulation in a county with a population of 275,000 or more, according to the 2020 federal
20 decennial census, shall allow by right the siting of no fewer than six dwelling units per acre.
21 (a3) Permitted Uses in Cities. – A city zoning regulation shall allow the following uses by
22 right:
23 (1) In areas zoned for residential use in a city with a population between 55,000
24 and 124,999, according to the 2020 federal decennial census, the siting of no
25 fewer than five dwelling units per acre.
26 (2) In areas zoned for residential use in a city with a population of 125,000 or
27 more, according to the 2020 federal decennial census, the siting of no fewer
28 than six dwelling units per acre.
29 (3) In areas zoned for non-agricultural commercial, business, or industrial use in
30 a city with a population of 125,000 or more, according to the 2020 federal
31 decennial census, the siting of buildings and structures subject to the North
32 Carolina Residential Code and multifamily housing structures with more than
33 four residential dwelling units, with a maximum height restriction of not less
34 than 60 feet.
35 (a4) Exemption from Building Design Elements and Buffer Yards. – In a city with a
36 population of 125,000 or more, according to the most recent decennial federal census, buildings
37 and structures subject to the North Carolina Residential Code and uses allowable under
38 subdivision (2) or (3) of subsection (a3) of this section shall not be subject to either of the
39 following:
40 (1) Building design elements as defined under G.S. 160D-702(b).
41 (2) Buffer yards or other landscape buffering regulations.
42 (a5) Applicability of Permitted Uses. – Subsections (a2) and (a3) of this section do not
43 apply to land used for a bona fide farm purpose as described in G.S. 160D-903 or an open space
44 land purpose as described in G.S. 160D-1307. Nothing in subsection (a2) or (a3) of this section
45 shall be construed to expand, diminish, or alter the scope of authority for planning, development,
46 or land use regulations set forth in Chapter 143 or Chapter 113A of the General Statutes.
47 However, to the extent a local government asserts that a parcel is subject to planning,
48 development, or land use standards authorized under Chapter 143 or Chapter 113A of the General
49 Statutes, the local government must support its determination with facts and information, other
50 than mere personal preferences or speculation, that a reasonable person would accept in support
