General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of its conclusion. Subsections (a2) and (a3) of this section apply regardless of whether the
2 dwelling units are located on multiple adjacent lots or a single lot.
3 (b) Conditional Districts. – Property may be placed in a conditional district only in
4 response to a petition by all owners of the property to be included. Specific conditions may be
5 proposed by the petitioner or the local government or its agencies, but only those conditions
6 approved by the local government and consented to by the petitioner in writing may be
7 incorporated into the zoning regulations. Unless consented to by the petitioner in writing,
8 Notwithstanding any other provision of law, in the exercise of the authority granted by this
9 section, a local government may not (i) require, enforce, or incorporate into the zoning
10 regulations any condition or requirement not authorized by otherwise applicable law, regulations
11 any condition, requirement, or deed restriction not specifically authorized by law, (ii) require,
12 enforce, or incorporate into the zoning regulations any condition or requirement that the courts
13 have held to be unenforceable if imposed directly by the local government, or (iii) accept any
14 offer by the petitioner to consent to any condition not specifically authorized by law, including,
15 without limitation, taxes, impact fees, building design elements within the scope of
16 G.S. 160D-702(b), driveway-related improvements in excess of those allowed in
17 G.S. 136-18(29) and G.S. 160A-307, or other unauthorized limitations on the development or
18 use of land. This subsection shall also apply to the approval of any site plan, development
19 agreement, conditional zoning permit, or any other instrument under this Chapter. Conditions
20 and site-specific standards imposed in a conditional district shall be limited to those that address
21 the conformance of the development and use of the site to local government ordinances, plans
22 adopted pursuant to G.S. 160D-501, or the impacts reasonably expected to be generated by the
23 development or use of the site. The zoning regulation may provide that defined minor
24 modifications in conditional district standards that do not involve a change in uses permitted or
25 the density of overall development permitted may be reviewed and approved administratively.
26 Any other modification of the conditions and standards in a conditional district shall follow the
27 same process for approval as are applicable to zoning map amendments. If multiple parcels of
28 land are subject to a conditional zoning, the owners of individual parcels may apply for
29 modification of the conditions so long as the modification would not result in other properties
30 failing to meet the terms of the conditions. Any modifications approved apply only to those
31 properties whose owners petition for the modification.
32 (b1) Limitations. – For parcels where multifamily structures are an allowable use, a local
33 government may not impose a harmony requirement for permit approval if the development
34 contains affordable housing units for families or individuals with incomes below eighty percent
35 (80%) of the area median income.
36 (c) Uniformity Within Districts. – Except as authorized by the foregoing, all zoning
37 regulations shall be uniform for each class or kind of building throughout each district but the
38 zoning regulations in one district may differ from those in other districts.
39 (d) Standards Applicable Regardless of District. – A zoning regulation or unified
40 development ordinance may also include development standards that apply uniformly
41 jurisdiction-wide rather than being applicable only in particular zoning districts.
42 (e) Staff Approvals. – Development approvals for a development that is a permitted use
43 in the zoning district where the development is located shall be made only by the designated staff
44 member as described in G.S. 160D-402.
45 (f) Basis for Conditional District. – In exercising its authority under subsection (b) of this
46 section, a local government shall support its determinations with facts and information, other
47 than mere personal preferences or speculation, that a reasonable person would accept in support
48 of a conclusion that there is a rational and substantial relationship between the conditional district
49 and the actual and legitimate needs of the community."
50 SECTION 13. Article 7 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
51 adding a new section to read:
Page 12 House Bill 765-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 160D-707. Review period for rezoning decisions.
2 Within 14 calendar days of the filing of an application for amendment of a zoning map or
3 zoning regulations, a local government or its designated administrative staff, as described under
4 G.S. 160D-402, shall (i) determine whether the application is complete and notify the applicant
5 of the application's completeness and, (ii) if the local government or its designated administrative
6 staff determines the application is incomplete, specify all the deficiencies in the notice to the
7 applicant. The applicant may file an amended application or supplemental information to cure
8 the deficiencies identified by the local government or its designated administrative staff for a
9 completeness review, which shall be completed within 14 calendar days after receiving an
10 amended application or supplemental application from the applicant. Upon the date the
11 application is deemed complete, the local government or its designated administrative staff shall
12 issue a receipt letter or electronic response stating that the application is complete and that a
13 90-calendar day review period has started as of that date. The local government shall approve or
14 deny the application within 90 calendar days of the date the application was deemed complete
15 by the local government or its designated administrative staff, except that if the applicant requests
16 a continuance of the application, the review period shall be tolled for the duration of any
17 continuance. The time period for review may be extended only by agreement with the applicant
18 if the application cannot be reviewed within the specified time limitation due to circumstances
19 beyond the control of the local government. The extension shall not exceed six months. Failure
20 of the local government or its designated administrative staff to act before the expiration of the
21 time period allowed for review shall constitute an approval of the application, and the local
22 government shall issue a written approval upon demand by the applicant."
