34 SECTION 17. Article 9 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
35 adding the following two new sections to read:
36 "§ 160D-974. Tiny houses in residential districts in certain cities.
37 (a) Tiny Housing in Residential Zones. – A city shall allow tiny housing in areas zoned
38 for residential or mixed-use residential, including those that allow for the development of
39 detached single-family dwellings.
40 (b) Regulation and Scope. – Nothing in this section affects the validity or enforceability
41 of private covenants or other contractual agreements among property owners relating to dwelling
42 type restrictions. Any development regulation adopted pursuant to this section shall not apply to
43 an area designated as a local historic district (i) pursuant to Part 4 of this Article or (ii) on the
44 National Register of Historic Places, unless approved by the local historic preservation authority.
45 For septic systems, a city may require a new system or an upgrade to an existing system if it is
46 determined that the existing system is incapable of handling increased capacity.
47 (c) Definitions. – As used in this section, the term "tiny housing" means a detached
48 single-family dwelling unit that is no greater than 600 square feet, built to standards applicable
49 to the North Carolina Residential Code, and is either constructed or mounted on a foundation and
50 is connected to utilities. The term does not include a recreational vehicle or manufactured home
51 that has not been affixed to real property.
House Bill 765-Third Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) Applicability. – This section applies only to cities with a population of 125,000 or
2 more, according to the most recent decennial federal census.
3 "§ 160D-975. Accessory dwelling units in certain cities.
4 (a) A city shall allow the development of at least one accessory dwelling unit which
5 conforms to the North Carolina Residential Code, including applicable provisions from the North
6 Carolina Fire Code, for each detached single-family dwelling that is greater than 600 square feet,
7 in areas zoned for residential use that allow for development of detached single-family dwellings.
8 An accessory dwelling unit may be built or sited concurrently with the primary dwelling or after
9 the primary dwelling has been constructed or sited. Nothing in this section shall prohibit a local
10 government from permitting accessory dwelling units in any area not otherwise required under
11 this section.
12 (b) Development and permitting of an accessory dwelling unit shall not be subject to any
13 of the following requirements:
14 (1) Owner-occupancy of any dwelling unit, including an accessory unit.
15 (2) Minimum parking requirements or other parking restrictions, including the
16 imposition of additional parking requirements where an existing structure is
17 converted for use as an accessory dwelling unit.
18 (3) Conditional use zoning.
19 (c) In permitting accessory dwelling units under this section, a city shall not do any of
20 the following:
21 (1) Prohibit the connection of the accessory dwelling unit to existing utilities
22 serving the primary dwelling unit.
23 (2) Charge any fee, other than a building permit fee, that exceeds the amount
24 charged for any single-family dwelling unit similar in nature.
25 (d) Except as otherwise provided in this section, a city may regulate accessory dwelling
26 units pursuant to this Chapter, provided that the development regulations do not act to discourage
27 development or siting of accessory dwelling units through unreasonable costs or delay. Nothing
28 in this section shall affect the validity or enforceability of private covenants or other contractual
29 agreements among property owners relating to dwelling type restrictions.
30 (e) A city may impose a setback minimum for accessory dwelling units of 5 feet or the
31 setback minimum imposed generally upon lots in the same zoning classification, whichever is
32 less.
33 (f) For the purposes of this section, the term "accessory dwelling unit" means an attached
34 or detached residential structure that is used in connection with or that is accessory to a primary
35 single-family dwelling and that has less total square footage than the primary single-family
36 dwelling.
37 (g) This section applies only to cities with a population of 125,000 or more, according to
38 the most recent decennial federal census."
39 SECTION 18. G.S. 160D-905 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 160D-905. Amateur radio antennas.
41 A local government ordinance based on health, safety, the actual and legitimate needs of the
42 community or aesthetic considerations that regulates the placement, screening, or height of the
43 antennas or support structures of amateur radio operators must reasonably accommodate amateur
44 radio communications and must represent the minimum practicable regulation necessary to
45 accomplish the purpose of the local government. A local government may not restrict antennas
46 or antenna support structures of amateur radio operators to heights of 90 feet or lower unless the
47 restriction is necessary to achieve a clearly defined health, safety, or aesthetic objective of the
48 local government."
