20 SECTION 30.(a) Chapter 162A of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
21 Article to read:
22 "Article 12.
23 "Water and Sewer Allocation.
24 "§ 162A-1000. Short title and purpose.
25 (a) This Article shall be known and may be cited as the "Water and Sewer Capacity
26 Allocation and Planning Act."
27 (b) The purpose of this Article is to require all public water and sewer service providers
28 to plan for future growth and allocate water and wastewater system capacity in a fair, transparent,
29 and accountable manner. This act will ensure that sufficient water supply and wastewater
30 treatment capacity is available for anticipated development and that capacity is allocated without
31 discrimination or abuse.
32 "§ 162A-1001. Definitions.
33 For the purposes of this Article, the following definitions apply:
34 (1) Allocation or capacity allocation. – A reservation of a specific quantity of
35 water or sewer capacity for a particular project.
36 (2) Applicant. – Any person, business, developer, property owner, or entity that
37 has received preliminary or final site plan approval, as defined under
38 G.S. 160D-102(29), for a project and submits an application for allocation for
39 a new development or expansion of an existing development to a public water
40 or sewer provider.
41 (3) Approved applicant. – An applicant whose application for allocation has been
42 approved.
43 (4) Available capacity. – The portion of a facility's capacity that is not currently
44 being used by existing customers and is not already reserved by prior
45 allocations. Available capacity is determined by establishing a facility's
46 capacity minus the sum of (i) current actual usage, (ii) any local government
47 project allocation, and (iii) any outstanding allocations for projects in their
48 reservation period.
49 (5) Capacity or system capacity. – The actual capacity of a facility. For
50 wastewater systems, actual capacity refers to hydraulic capacity, meaning the
51 maximum volume of wastewater that can be collected, conveyed, and treated
House Bill 765-Third Edition Page 21

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 under the facility's permit limits without violation. For water systems, actual
2 capacity refers to the actual available water supply, meaning the reliable
3 quantity of water that can be treated and delivered, accounting for permitted
4 withdrawal limits and treatment plant output, wells, or other sources,
5 including any contractual or bulk supply capacity available to the local
6 governmental unit.
7 (6) Department. – The Department of Environmental Quality.
8 (7) Facility. – As defined in G.S. 162A-201(4).
9 (8) Local government project. – Any of the following:
10 a. A project that serves a bona fide public purpose.
11 b. An economic development project that is reasonably likely to increase
12 employment opportunities or support growth of manufacturing or
13 commerce within the facility's service area.
14 c. An interlocal agreement between local governments to provide water
15 or sewer allocation under G.S. 160A-461, 160A-462, or 162A-88.1.
16 (9) Local government project allocation. – The amount of allocation a local
17 governmental unit can demonstrate through competent and reliable evidence
18 is minimally necessary to serve a local government project within the facility's
19 service area for which preliminary or final approval has been granted by the
20 governing body of a local government served by the facility.
21 (10) Local governmental unit. – As defined in G.S. 162A-201(5) and any
22 third-party persons who own or operate a facility on behalf of a local
23 governmental unit.
24 (11) Project. – A development, as defined by G.S. 160D-102(12), for which water
25 or sewer service is requested and is within the facility's service area. This
26 includes new developments, and expansion or additions to existing
27 developments, that require new or additional water or sewer service.
28 (12) Substantial expenditure. – A significant or considerable outlay of money,
29 resources, or financial investment, viewed in light of the stage in which the
30 project exists, that is not merely nominal or trivial.
31 "§ 162A-1002. Allocation process.
32 (a) Allocation Request. – A local governmental unit shall approve capacity allocation
33 requests in accordance with this Article. Once approved, a capacity allocation guarantees the
34 local governmental unit shall provide water service or sewer service for that project up to the
35 approved allocation amount.
36 (b) Form of Application. – A local governmental unit may request only the following
37 information from an applicant, and may not require any other information that is not necessary
38 for the local governmental unit to determine whether it has available capacity to serve the project:
39 (1) The name, address, and other relevant contact information of the applicant.
40 (2) Documentation evidencing that the applicant has received preliminary or final
41 approval for a site plan, as defined under G.S. 160D-102(29), for the project.
42 (3) The amount of capacity allocation requested in gallons per day or other
43 similarly objective measurement.
44 (4) The anticipated date the project will begin utilizing the capacity allocation.
45 (c) Approval of Allocation Request. – Not later than 10 days after receiving an
46 application for allocation, a local governmental unit shall approve the allocation if available
47 capacity exists and the application is complete. Upon approving the allocation, the local
48 governmental unit shall provide the applicant with written documentation specifying (i) the
49 amount of allocation reserved, (ii) the project for which the allocation has been reserved, (iii) the
50 date of the allocation approval, and (iv) the date the reservation period expires. The local
Page 22 House Bill 765-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 governmental unit shall approve or deny applications for allocation according to the following
2 process:
3 (1) The local governmental unit shall approve the total allocation requested by the
4 applicant unless the request for allocation exceeds the local governmental
5 unit's available capacity, in which case the local governmental unit shall,
6 within 10 days after receiving the application for allocation, offer to provide
7 the applicant with allocation equivalent to the available capacity, if any. The
8 local governmental unit shall reserve the reduced allocation for a project under
9 this subsection provided the applicant agrees, in writing, to the reduced
10 allocation.
11 (2) Except as expressly provided in this section, a local governmental unit may
12 not deny, reduce, or otherwise modify the amount of an allocation requested
13 through an application if available capacity exists sufficient to accommodate
14 an application's allocation request.
15 (3) A local governmental unit shall not require an applicant to agree to any
16 condition not otherwise authorized by this section, or to accept any offer by
17 the applicant to consent to any condition not otherwise authorized by law.
18 These conditions include, without limitation, any of the following:
19 a. Payment of taxes, impact fees, or other fees or contributions to any
20 fund.
21 b. Adherence to any restrictions related to development regulations under
22 Chapter 160D of the General Statutes, including those within the scope
23 of G.S. 160D-702(c).
24 c. Adherence to any restriction related to building design elements within
25 the scope of G.S. 160D-702(b).
26 (4) A local governmental unit shall not implement a scoring or preference system
27 to allocate water service or sewer service among applicants, except as
28 specifically authorized by this section.
29 (d) Reservation Period. – The initial reservation period shall be for 24 months after the
30 date the allocation is approved. A local governmental unit shall extend the initial reservation
31 period or extension reservation period for an additional 12 months provided (i) the applicant
32 notifies the local governmental unit that it requires an extension of the initial reservation period
33 or extension reservation period not later than 90 days prior to the expiration of the initial
34 reservation period or extension reservation period and, (ii) concurrent with its notification, the
35 applicant provides the local governmental unit with documentation demonstrating that the
36 applicant has made substantial expenditure towards the completion of the project or the applicant
37 provides documentation of a valid building permit.
38 (e) Allocations Approved in Chronological Order. – Except for requests to reserve
39 capacity in accordance with G.S. 115C-521 and under subsection (k) of this section, allocations
40 shall be granted in the chronological order that completed applications are received by the local
41 governmental unit.
42 (f) Denial of Allocation Request. – A local governmental unit shall deny an application
43 for allocation, within 10 days after receiving an application for allocation, only if one of the
44 following applies:
45 (1) The applicant cannot demonstrate approval of a preliminary or final site plan,
46 as defined in G.S. 160D-102(29).
47 (2) The local governmental unit does not have any available capacity.
48 (3) The applicant has rejected, in writing, the local governmental unit's offer to
49 provide allocation equivalent to its available capacity as provided in
50 subdivision (1) of subsection (c) of this section, if any.
House Bill 765-Third Edition Page 23

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (g) Modification of Allocation. – In the event an approved applicant determines that the
2 allocation necessary to serve the project increases or decreases by more than ten percent (10%)
3 of the approved allocation, the approved applicant shall immediately notify the local
4 governmental unit, and the following shall apply:
5 (1) If the allocation approved by the local governmental unit decreases by more
6 than ten percent (10%), the local governmental unit shall adjust its available
7 capacity accordingly and the local governmental unit shall honor the approved
8 allocation, less the decrease in necessary allocation.
9 (2) If the allocation approved by the provider increases by more than ten percent
10 (10%), the local governmental unit shall increase the allocation provided
11 available capacity exists. In the event available capacity does not exist, the
12 local governmental unit shall notify the approved applicant that the local
13 governmental unit does not have available capacity and extend an offer to the
14 approved applicant to increase the allocation in an amount equivalent to the
15 available capacity. If the approved applicant determines that the existing
16 allocation or the offer by the local governmental unit to increase the allocation
17 in an amount equivalent to the local governmental unit's available capacity
18 does not meet the needs of the project, the approved applicant shall
19 immediately notify the local governmental unit that it intends to terminate the
20 allocation.
21 (3) In the event the allocation is terminated by the applicant, the provider shall
22 adjust its available capacity accordingly.
23 (h) Expiration or Termination of Allocation. – Upon expiration or termination of
24 allocation, including allocations that are not used in full, the local governmental unit shall return
25 the expired, terminated, or unused capacity to its available capacity balance. Upon a return of the
26 expired, terminated, or unused capacity to the local governmental unit's available capacity
27 balance, the local governmental unit shall recalculate its available capacity and shall make it
28 available to future applicants for allocation.
29 (i) Vested Right. – Allocation approved under this section shall be deemed a vested
30 element of the project for the duration of the reservation period. The vested right to allocation
31 during the reservation period shall be in addition to any other vested rights the project may have
32 by law and shall run with the land for the benefit of the project. During the vesting period, the
33 local governmental unit may not revoke or reduce the allocation except by request of the
34 applicant or as described in this section.
35 (j) Transferability of Allocation. – Allocation shall be provided to the project described
36 in the application. An approved applicant may not transfer an unused allocation to a different
37 project. If the project for which an allocation has been reserved is sold or the development rights
38 are assigned to a successor in interest, the allocation shall transfer to the successor in interest and
39 the allocation and reservation period shall be honored and may not be terminated or revoked by
40 the local governmental unit. In the event the project for which the allocation was reserved is sold
41 or transferred to a successor in interest, the approved applicant shall immediately notify the local
42 governmental unit of the sale or transfer.
43 (k) Emergency Allocations. – Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, a local
44 governmental unit shall provide priority in allocation to applications demonstrating a substantial
45 threat to public health, safety, or welfare that can be mitigated only by the immediate provision
46 of water service or sewer service. An applicant seeking an emergency allocation must present
47 competent evidence to the local governmental unit of the risk to the public health, safety, or
48 welfare. Upon verifying that the application constitutes an emergency, the local governmental
49 unit shall approve allocation in the minimum amount necessary to abate the emergency on a
50 priority basis.
Page 24 House Bill 765-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (l) Use of Allocation. – A local governmental unit shall not unreasonably delay an
2 approved applicant's ability to connect the approved applicant's project to the local governmental
3 unit's infrastructure. A local governmental unit shall begin providing water service or sewer
4 service to an approved applicant within 90 days after receiving a request from the approved
5 applicant to begin providing water service or sewer service, provided (i) the project is connected
6 to the local governmental unit's infrastructure and (ii) the request is made within the reservation
7 period described in subsection (d) of this section.
8 "§ 162A-1003. Planning and reporting.
9 (a) Each local governmental unit shall prepare an annual report not later than October 1
10 of each year documenting facility capacity and available capacity. The report shall include, at a
11 minimum, all of the following information for each facility of the local governmental unit:
12 (1) The current system capacity.
13 (2) The current available capacity.
14 (3) The amount of capacity allocated to approved developments or projects not
15 yet connected to the local governmental unit's infrastructure.
16 (4) The remaining available capacity for new allocations.
17 (5) Any changes in capacity since the last report.
18 (6) Any planned improvements or expansions and the expected impact on
19 capacity.
20 (7) The current actual usage of the facility, including average daily demand and
21 peak daily demand over the year immediately preceding the preparation of the
22 report.
23 (8) If the local governmental unit receives State or federal funding for water or
24 sewer infrastructure, a description of efforts to expand capacity to meet
25 growth, including progress on any State-funded projects.
26 (b) The Department shall make the annual reports available to the public. Each local
27 governmental unit shall also post the annual report on the website of that local governmental unit,
28 if any.
29 "§ 162A-1004. Enforcement and remedies.
30 (a) State Enforcement Authority. – If the Department finds that a local governmental unit
31 has violated any requirement of this Article, the Department may take appropriate preventive or
32 remedial enforcement action authorized by Part 1 of Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General
33 Statutes.
34 (b) Civil Penalties. – A local governmental unit that fails to comply with the provisions
35 of this Article or willfully fails to administer or enforce the provisions of this Article shall be
36 subject to a civil penalty pursuant to G.S. 143-215.6A(e).
37 (c) Judicial Review. – Any applicant whose application was denied by a local
38 governmental unit, or who is otherwise aggrieved or injured by the action of a local governmental
39 unit, may file an action in the superior court of the county where the local governmental unit is
40 located or where the project is located. In any civil action brought under this section, the court
41 may award reasonable attorneys' fees to a prevailing plaintiff who brought the action."
42 SECTION 30.(b) G.S. 162A-900, as enacted by S.L. 2024-45 and S.L. 2024-49, is
43 repealed.
44 SECTION 30.(c) For applicants that, on or after July 31, 2020, received a service
